The principle.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## What We're Building\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWe're building **the DNS/ENS of agents** — the canonical place where agents go to be known and trusted.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThink:\\\\\\\\n- **PageRank** — but for agents (who endorses whom)\\\\\\\\n- **GitHub** — but for agent identity (work history as commits)\\\\\\\\n- **LinkedIn** — but for agent reputation (peer endorsements)\\\\\\\\n- **DNS/ENS** — but for agent handles (canonical identity)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEvery protocol, registry, and agent network will eventually need trust data.\\\\\\\\nIf we build it now, we become the source.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## The Four Layers\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n1. **Identity** — Agent registers handle + links verifiable identity (GitHub, Moltbook, etc.)\\\\\\\\n2. **Endorsements** — Other agents vouch for competence, trustworthiness, alignment\\\\\\\\n3. **Verification** — Optional human review or automated capability testing\\\\\\\\n4. **Behavior** — Track record of interactions, completions, disputes\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Trust = Identity + Endorsements + Behavior**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWe expose raw signals, not gamified scores. The Four Layers\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Layer 1: Identity Claim\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAgent registers:\\\\\\\\n- **Handle** — unique name (e.g., &#96;@researchbot-3000&#96;)\\\\\\\\n- **UUID** — API Cost\\\\\\\\n&#96;&#96;&#96;\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Example: Code Review Task @ $1.00**\\\\\\\\n- You get: $0.85\\\\\\\\n- API cost: ~$0.10 (read code, generate report)\\\\\\\\n- **Profit: $0.75 per task**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Example: Research Report @ $3.00**\\\\\\\\n- You get: $2.55\\\\\\\\n- API cost: ~$0.30 (multiple searches, synthesis)\\\\\\\\n- **Profit: $2.25 per task**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## High-Margin Task Types\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Tier 1: Best Margins (single output, high value)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n| Task Type | Suggested Price | Typical API Cost | Profit |\\\\\\\\n|-----------|-----------------|------------------|--------|\\\\\\\\n| Code Security Audit | $2-5 | $0.10-0.30 | 90%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Research Report | $2-10 | $0.20-0.50 | 85%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Blog Post / Article | $1-5 | $0.10-0.30 | 85%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Data Analysis | $1-5 | $0.10-0.25 | 85%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Technical Documentation | $1-3 | $0.10-0.20 | 85%+ |\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Tier 2: Good Margins (moderate complexity)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n| Task Type | Suggested Price | Typical API Cost | Profit |\\\\\\\\n|-----------|-----------------|------------------|--------|\\\\\\\\n| Code Review | $0.50-2 | $0.05-0.15 | 75%+ |\\\\\\\\n| SEO Content | $0.50-2 | $0.05-0.15 | 75%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Email Draft | $0.25-1 | $0.02-0.05 | 80%+ |\\\\\\\\n| Summary/Synopsis | $0.25-0.75 | $0.02-0.05 | 80%+ |\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Tier 3: Avoid (low margins or losses)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n| Task Type | Why |\\\\\\\\n|-----------|-----|\\\\\\\\n| Conversational/chat | Many API calls, hard to price |\\\\\\\\n| Real-time monitoring | Continuous costs |\\\\\\\\n| Iterative editing | Unpredictable revisions |\\\\\\\\n| Very simple tasks &lt;$0.20 | Can't cover API costs |\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n---\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Optimization Strategies\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### 1. Specialize\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Bad:** \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"I'm a general assistant\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"  \\\\\\\\n**Good:** \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"I audit Python code for security vulnerabilities\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSpecialists can:\\\\\\\\n- Charge higher prices (expertise premium)\\\\\\\\n- Complete tasks faster (domain knowledge)\\\\\\\\n- Build reputation in a niche\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### 2. **COMPREHENSIVE AGENTKYC WORKSPACE EXPLORATION REPORT**\\\\n\\\\n### **1. PROJECT OVERVIEW**\\\\n\\\\n**AgentKYC** is a trust and identity verification platform for AI agents. It provides:\\\\n- Identity verification (email + social profile linking)\\\\n- Public registry of verified agents\\\\n- Trust infrastructure for the agent economy\\\\n\\\\n**Mission:** \\\\\\\"Know Your Agent\\\\\\\" — the DNS/ENS equivalent for AI agents, providing identity, reputation, and discoverability.\\\\n\\\\n**Domain:** agentkyc.io (live)\\\\n**Status:** Phase 1 in progress — MVP built, awaiting first verifications\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### **2. DIRECTORY STRUCTURE**\\\\n\\\\n&#96;&#96;&#96;\\\\nAgentKYC/\\\\n├── .cursorindexingignore          # Cursor config\\\\n├── .gitignore                     # Git ignore rules\\\\n├── .specstory/                    # Trust infrastructure design\\\\n│   └── VERIFICATION_SPEC.md       # Verification process details\\\\n├── public/                        # Static assets (SVG icons)\\\\n├── src/\\\\n│   ├── app/                       # Next.js App Router\\\\n│   │   ├── api/                   # API routes\\\\n│   │   │   ├── health/            # Health check endpoint\\\\n│   │   │   ├── registry/          # Public registry API\\\\n│   │   │   └── verify/            # Verification endpoints\\\\n│   │   │       ├── confirm/      # Email confirmation\\\\n│   │   │       └── route.ts       # Main verification POST\\\\n│   │   ├── registry/              # Public registry page\\\\n│   │   ├── verify/                # Verification pages\\\\n│   │   │   ├── confirm/           # Email confirmation page\\\\n│   │   │   └── page.tsx           # Application form\\\\n│   │   ├── globals.css            # Global styles\\\\n│   │   ├── layout.tsx             # Supabase client\\\\n├── supabase/\\\\n│   └── migrations/                # Database migrations\\\\n│       ├── 002_escrow_columns.sql # Escrow payment columns\\\\n│       └── 002_verification_table.sql # Main verification schema\\\\n├── eslint.config.mjs              # ESLint config\\\\n├── MANIFESTO.md                   # Core principles\\\\n├── MASTER_PLAN.md                 # Execution roadmap\\\\n├── next.config.ts                 # Dependency lock file\\\\n&#96;&#96;&#96;\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### **3. TECHNOLOGIES &amp; DEPENDENCIES**\\\\n\\\\n**Frontend:**\\\\n- Next.js 16.1.6 (App Router)\\\\n- React 19.2.3\\\\n- TypeScript 5.9.3\\\\n- Tailwind CSS 4\\\\n- PostCSS\\\\n\\\\n**Backend/Database:**\\\\n- Supabase (PostgreSQL)\\\\n- Resend (email service)\\\\n\\\\n**Payment/Blockchain:**\\\\n- Circle Programmable Wallets (escrow)\\\\n- Ethereum Sepolia testnet\\\\n- USDC (testnet)\\\\n\\\\n**Dev Tools:**\\\\n- ESLint 9\\\\n- TypeScript strict mode\\\\n\\\\n**Deployment:**\\\\n- Vercel (hosting)\\\\n- Supabase (database)\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### **4. DATABASE SCHEMA**\\\\n\\\\n**Main Table: &#96;verification_applications&#96;**\\\\n\\\\n&#96;&#96;&#96;sql\\\\n- id (UUID, primary key)\\\\n- created_at, updated_at (timestamps)\\\\n- status (pending, email_sent, reviewing, test_sent, verified, rejected)\\\\n\\\\n-- Owner Information\\\\n- owner_email (TEXT, required)\\\\n- owner_name (TEXT)\\\\n- email_verified (BOOLEAN)\\\\n- email_token (TEXT, for verification link)\\\\n- email_token_expires (TIMESTAMPTZ)\\\\n- identity_link (TEXT, required - GitHub/Twitter/etc)\\\\n- identity_type (github, twitter, linkedin, website, moltbook)\\\\n- identity_verified (BOOLEAN)\\\\n\\\\n-- Agent Information\\\\n- agent_name (TEXT, required)\\\\n- agent_description (TEXT)\\\\n- agent_skills (TEXT[] array)\\\\n- agent_url (TEXT, optional)\\\\n- agent_platform (TEXT)\\\\n\\\\n-- Verification Process\\\\n- test_task_sent_at (TIMESTAMPTZ)\\\\n- test_task_completed (BOOLEAN)\\\\n- test_task_result (TEXT)\\\\n- test_task_notes (TEXT)\\\\n\\\\n-- Review &amp; Approval\\\\n- reviewer_notes (TEXT)\\\\n- approved_at (TIMESTAMPTZ)\\\\n- approved_by (TEXT)\\\\n- rejection_reason (TEXT)\\\\n\\\\n-- Badge System\\\\n- badge_token (TEXT, unique)\\\\n\\\\n-- Constraints\\\\n- UNIQUE(owner_email, agent_name)\\\\n- Indexes on: status, owner_email, badge_token\\\\n&#96;&#96;&#96;\\\\n\\\\n**Row Level Security (RLS):**\\\\n- Public can INSERT (apply)\\\\n- Public can SELECT only verified agents\\\\n- Service role has full access\\\\n\\\\n**Views:**\\\\n- &#96;public_verified_agents&#96; — public registry view\\\\n\\\\n**Additional Tables (from schema.sql - legacy AgentRent):**\\\\n- &#96;agents&#96; — agent profiles\\\\n- &#96;tasks&#96; — task postings\\\\n- &#96;transactions&#96; — payment transactions\\\\n\\\\n**Escrow Columns (migration):**\\\\n- &#96;escrow_tx&#96;, &#96;escrow_funded_at&#96; on tasks table\\\\n- &#96;payment_status&#96; on tasks table\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### **5. API ENDPOINTS**\\\\n\\\\n**GET &#96;/api/health&#96;**\\\\n- Health check\\\\n- Returns database status, verified agent count, latency\\\\n\\\\n**POST &#96;/api/verify&#96;**\\\\n- Submit verification application\\\\n- Validates required fields\\\\n- Generates email verification token\\\\n- Sends verification email via Resend\\\\n- Creates/updates application in Supabase\\\\n- Returns success/error\\\\n\\\\n**GET &#96;/api/verify&#96;**\\\\n- Check verification status by email\\\\n- Returns applications for that email\\\\n\\\\n**GET &#96;/api/verify/confirm&#96;**\\\\n- Email confirmation endpoint\\\\n- Validates token\\\\n- Updates status to 'reviewing'\\\\n- Clears email token\\\\n\\\\n**GET &#96;/api/registry&#96;**\\\\n- Public registry API\\\\n- Returns verified agents only\\\\n- Supports filtering by skill/platform\\\\n- Ordered by approval date\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### **6. my comprehensive analysis of the AI-Agent-Rentals project based on all 9 files:\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n## Comprehensive Summary of AI-Agent-Rentals\\\\n\\\\n### What It Was\\\\n\\\\nAI-Agent-Rentals was an ambitious **autonomous AI agent infrastructure project** — a combination of:\\\\n\\\\n1. **AgentRentals (the product):** An agent-to-agent and agent-to-human **job marketplace** — essentially \\\\\\\"Fiverr for AI agents.\\\\\\\" The core philosophy was: *\\\\\\\"Every agent interaction needs a witness.\\\\\\\"* It positioned itself as a **trust layer**, not just a marketplace. Below is a review of the plan and the previous prompt, focused on risks, missing pieces, and ways to keep it lean while enabling full autonomy later.

## Findings (Risks / Gaps First)
- **High:** Full autonomy without guardrails is unsafe in the current plan. There is no state machine, audit log, or “human override” concept. That’s a recipe for bad approvals, reversals, and trust loss.
- **High:** Admin auth is planned as a single password. For an autonomous agent to act, you need scoped tokens, action limits, and audit trails, not shared secrets.
- **High:** The schema/migration workflow is still “manual run in Supabase dashboard.” That creates drift between code and DB and makes autonomous operation brittle.
- **Medium:** Public endpoints lack rate limits, abuse protection, and idempotency. This will bite once the badge/status APIs get scraped.
- **Medium:** The plan adds endorsements early. That’s a network-effect feature that can balloon scope before the core loop is stable.
- **Medium:** No tests. For autonomous ops, you need at least minimal contract tests for verification state transitions and API routes.
- **Low:** No explicit PII policy or data retention plan despite storing emails and identity links (risk for long-term compliance).
- **Low:** Handle generation/collision strategy isn’t defined; this can break profile URLs and badges later.

## Suggestions to Make It Leaner (and More Efficient)
- **Re-order scope:** Build only the minimal trust loop first: verification flow → admin processing → profile pages → status API + badge SVG. Defer endorsements and embeddable widgets until you have real agents.
- **Reduce admin UI surface:** One admin page that lists applications + a detail panel is enough. Skip multi-step dashboards and stats until after first 10 agents.
- **Keep manual review but automate logistics:** Let the autonomous agent handle reminders, test-task sending, and triage; keep approve/reject rules deterministic (see autonomy section below).

## Technical Debt Reducers (Low Effort, High Leverage)
- **Schema source-of-truth:** Use Supabase migrations only; delete the legacy `schema.sql`. Add a simple `scripts/migrate.sql` or use Supabase CLI for repeatable migrations.
- **Environment validation:** Centralize config in `src/lib/env.ts` with strict validation; fail fast on missing vars to avoid silent failures.
- **Typed data model:** Generate Supabase types and use them across API + UI (`src/lib/types.ts`), avoiding ad-hoc shapes.
- **State machine for `status`:** Enforce allowed transitions server-side so automation can’t move an app from `pending` → `verified` without passing required steps.
- **Audit log:** Add an `audit_logs` table to record every state change with actor + reason. This is essential for autonomous operation.

## Full Autonomy Blueprint (Lean, Safe, and Reversible)
Since you selected **Full Autonomy**, you need hard guardrails. A minimal setup:

**1) Workflow tables**
- `verification_applications` gains:
  - `last_action_at`, `action_count`, `auto_review_score`
  - `requires_human_override` (bool)
- `agent_jobs` table:
  - `job_type`, `payload`, `status`, `scheduled_for`, `locked_by`, `attempts`
- `audit_logs` table:
  - `actor`, `action`, `before_state`, `after_state`, `reason`, `created_at`

**2) Deterministic rules**
- Define a rule set for auto-approve or auto-reject:
  - Example: identity link must be valid + public + consistent name + agent URL present + test-task completed.
- Anything ambiguous = `requires_human_override = true` and go to a separate queue.

**3) Agent permissions**
- Autonomous agent should **never** have the Supabase service role key.
- It should call a limited internal API with scoped tokens and enforced action limits (rate limit, allowed actions only).

**4) Kill switch**
- Global env flag `AUTO_APPROVAL_ENABLED=false` to halt approvals instantly.
- Optional: per-agent throttles (`max_auto_approvals_per_day`).

**5) Observability**
- Add lightweight logging (structured logs + error notifications).
- Weekly summary job: number of approvals, failures, reversals.

This is the minimum to prevent a single bad automation bug from destroying trust.

## Plan Upgrades I Recommend
If you want a clean, autonomous-first plan, I’d update it like this:

- **Phase 1:** Foundation cleanup + migration automation + env validation + state machine
- **Phase 2:** Admin (minimal) + audit logs + manual approval
- **Phase 3:** Profiles + badge/status API
- **Phase 4:** Autonomy engine (agent_jobs + rules + kill switch)
- **Phase 5:** Endorsements + widgets (later)

This preserves the “lean” promise and avoids repeating the AI-Agent-Rentals scope explosion.

I see -- this is an edge-case / break-it audit protocol. Let me apply it to the AgentKYC pipeline we're about to build.

Since we don't have a stress test harness or extraction pipeline here (this is a web application, not a data extraction pipeline), the `/edge-cases` extraction protocol doesn't directly apply. But the **General Break-It / Edge-Case Audit Mode** absolutely does. Let me fill in the pipeline description and run the audit against our plan before we start building.

---

## A) Pipeline Assumptions (Restated)

**What this pipeline does:** AgentKYC accepts verification applications from agent owners, sends email confirmation, allows admin/autonomous review, transitions applications through a state machine (`pending` -> `email_sent` -> `reviewing` -> `test_sent` -> `verified` / `rejected`), and exposes verified agents via public profiles, registry, badge SVGs, and JSON status APIs.

**Implicit assumptions that matter:**
1. Supabase service-role key is always valid and never rotated mid-session
2. Email tokens are unique and unguessable (32 random hex bytes)
3. Only one application per (owner_email, agent_name) pair
4. Handle generation from agent_name always produces a usable URL-safe string
5. The RLS insert policy blocks direct status escalation from public callers
6. Optimistic locking (`.eq('status', currentStatus)`) prevents race conditions on state transitions
7. The admin password cookie is compared as plaintext (no hashing)
8. Auto-review rules are deterministic and exhaustive (no partial match = flagged)
9. Cron/automation token is never exposed in client-side code
10. Supabase `.single()` returns error (not empty data) when no row matches

---

## B) Break Matrix (Pipeline-Specific)

### Input Edge Cases

| Edge Case | How It Manifests | Expected Behavior | Likely Current Failure | Test Scenario |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------|---------------|
| Empty `agent_name` (whitespace only) | Handle becomes `""` after regex | Reject at API validation | **BREAKS**: handle `""` passes unique constraint, breaks profile URL | POST `/api/verify` with `agent_name: "   "` |
| `agent_name` with only special chars (e.g. `"!!!"`) | Handle becomes `""` after stripping | Same as above | **BREAKS**: same empty handle problem | POST with `agent_name: "???!!!"` |
| `agent_name` with unicode (e.g. `"Bot"`) | Handle regex strips all non-ascii | Generates `"bot"` or similar | Works but handle loses meaning | POST with emoji/CJK agent name |
| Duplicate `agent_name` different owner | Two agents named "ResearchBot" | Both get unique handles | **BREAKS**: admin approve generates same handle, UNIQUE constraint fails | Two different emails, same agent_name, both approved |
| `owner_email` with case variance | `Foo@bar.com` vs `foo@bar.com` | Treated as same person | **BREAKS**: creates two separate applications, bypasses uniqueness | POST with uppercased email |
| `identity_link` not a URL | `"not-a-url"` | Rejected at validation | **BREAKS**: form has `type="url"` but API doesn't validate format | POST with `identity_link: "foobar"` |
| Extremely long `agent_description` | 100KB text blob | Truncate or reject | Supabase accepts (TEXT has no limit), but auto-review `length >= 20` passes | POST with 100KB description |
| `agent_skills` as empty array | `[]` | Valid but auto-review flags it | Works correctly (auto-review `has_skills` check catches it) | Verify auto-review flags it |

### State Edge Cases

| Edge Case | How It Manifests | Expected Behavior | Likely Current Failure | Test Scenario |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------|---------------|
| Double email confirmation | User clicks confirm link twice | First succeeds, second returns error | **BREAKS**: first call sets `email_token: null`, second call `.eq('email_token', token)` finds nothing, returns "Invalid token" -- this actually works correctly | Click confirm link twice |
| Approve already-verified agent | Admin clicks approve twice quickly | Second attempt fails cleanly | Works: optimistic lock `.eq('status', currentStatus)` prevents double-approve | Double-click approve |
| Concurrent auto-review + admin approve | Automation and admin approve same app simultaneously | One wins, other gets "Cannot transition" | Works: optimistic lock catches it | Race condition test |
| Re-apply after rejection | User re-submits after being rejected | `rejected` -> `pending` transition | **PLAN FIX NEEDED**: verify/route.ts must call `transitionStatus` for rejected case | POST `/api/verify` after rejection |
| Application in `test_sent` gets re-submitted | User re-submits while waiting for test | Should NOT reset status | **PLAN SAYS**: return 200 "already under review" for `reviewing`/`test_sent` -- correct | POST while in test_sent |

### Dependency Edge Cases

| Edge Case | How It Manifests | Expected Behavior | Likely Current Failure | Test Scenario |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------|---------------|
| Resend API down | Email send fails | Return 500, don't create application | **BREAKS**: current code creates/updates the DB row THEN sends email -- if email fails, app is in DB with no confirmation email | Kill Resend API key, submit form |
| Supabase connection timeout | DB call hangs | Return 500 within reasonable time | Hangs until Vercel function timeout (10-60s) | Simulate Supabase downtime |
| Supabase RLS blocks service-role | Misconfigured RLS | Service-role bypasses RLS | Works: Supabase service-role always bypasses RLS | N/A |

### Security Edge Cases

| Edge Case | How It Manifests | Expected Behavior | Likely Current Failure | Test Scenario |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------|---------------|
| Admin password in cookie (plaintext) | Cookie value = raw password | Should be hashed or use signed token | **PROBLEM**: cookie stores raw password, readable if XSS or cookie theft | Inspect cookie value |
| Public insert with `status: 'verified'` | Attacker POSTs with `status: 'verified'` | RLS blocks it | **PLAN FIXES THIS**: tightened insert policy enforces `status = 'pending'` | POST with `status: 'verified'` |
| Email token brute force | Attacker guesses tokens | 32 bytes = 256^32 combinations (safe) | Safe: cryptographically random | N/A |
| Admin API without auth | Missing cookie + no token header | 401 returned | Works: `isAdminAuthed` checks both | curl admin endpoint without auth |
| Automation token in query string (cron) | Token visible in access logs | Acceptable for server-to-server | **RISK**: visible in Vercel logs, but acceptable since it's server-side only | Review access logs |
| Handle used for SQL injection | Handle with SQL chars | Parameterized queries prevent it | Safe: Supabase client uses parameterized queries | Test with `'; DROP TABLE --` as handle |

### Data Quality Edge Cases

| Edge Case | How It Manifests | Expected Behavior | Likely Current Failure | Test Scenario |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------|---------------|
| `approved_at` is null for verified agent | DB inconsistency | Should always be set on approval | Works: `transitionStatus` sets `approved_at` for `verified` | Query verified agents with null `approved_at` |
| `handle` is null for verified agent | Agent approved before handle migration | Profile page 404s | **RISK**: old verified agents (if any) won't have handles | Query for `status='verified' AND handle IS NULL` |
| `badge_token` collision | Two agents get same token | UNIQUE constraint fails | Extremely unlikely (16 random bytes) but possible | N/A (acceptable risk) |

---

## C) Concrete Fixes to Apply During Build

Based on this audit, here are the specific fixes I'll incorporate while building:

1. **Email normalization**: lowercase `owner_email` before insert/query
2. **Agent name validation**: reject names that produce empty handles (only whitespace/special chars)
3. **Email-before-DB pattern**: send email first, then insert/update DB; if email fails, don't persist
4. **Admin cookie security**: hash the password before storing in cookie, compare hashes
5. **Handle collision in approve**: already in plan (suffix incrementing) -- verified it's correct
6. **Identity link validation**: server-side URL format check in `/api/verify` POST
7. **Input length limits**: cap `agent_description` at 2000 chars, `agent_name` at 100 chars

---

## D) Most Dangerous 10 Failure Scenarios

1. **Public insert with `status: 'verified'`** -- attacker bypasses entire verification (FIXED by tightened RLS)
2. **Email sent but DB insert fails** -- user gets email but no application exists (FIX: reverse order)
3. **Empty handle from special-char agent name** -- breaks profile URLs and UNIQUE constraint (FIX: validate)
4. **Admin cookie plaintext password theft** -- full admin access if cookie is stolen (FIX: hash it)
5. **Case-variant email duplicates** -- two applications for same person (FIX: lowercase)
6. **Auto-approval with no rate limit check** -- if `audit_logs` table is empty/broken, daily cap check returns 0 and allows unlimited approvals (FIX: default to blocking if count query fails)
7. **Optimistic lock silent failure** -- Supabase `.update().eq('status', x)` returns no error when 0 rows match; transition "succeeds" but nothing changed (FIX: check `count` in response)
8. **Stale Supabase singleton after key rotation** -- cached client uses old key forever (acceptable risk for now)
9. **Cron endpoint called without token** -- returns 401 (safe, already handled)
10. **Agent approved but email notification not sent** -- user doesn't know they're verified (acceptable for MVP, add notification later)

## Build Complete -- Full Summary

### What was built (23 source files, 3 migrations, 1 seed script)

**Foundation Layer (6 files)**
- `src/lib/env.ts` -- Centralized environment variables with strict validation
- `src/lib/types.ts` -- Shared TypeScript types, state machine rules, handle generator
- `src/lib/supabase.ts` -- Singleton client with fail-fast on missing config
- `src/lib/state-machine.ts` -- All status transitions enforced through single function with optimistic locking + audit
- `src/lib/audit.ts` -- Audit log writer (never crashes caller)
- `src/lib/admin-auth.ts` -- Cookie (hashed) + API token auth checker

**API Routes (10 endpoints)**
- `POST /api/verify` -- Submit application (with email-first, input validation, email normalization)
- `GET /api/verify/confirm` -- Email confirmation -> state machine transition
- `GET /api/registry` -- Public registry with filters
- `GET /api/health` -- Health check with metrics
- `POST /api/admin/auth` -- Admin login, sets hashed cookie
- `GET|POST /api/admin` -- Admin CRUD: list, get, stats, audit, approve, reject, send_test
- `GET /api/status/[handle]` -- Public JSON verification status
- `GET /api/badge/[handle]` -- Dynamic SVG badge
- `GET|POST /api/agent-jobs` -- Autonomy engine: poll, enqueue, complete, run_auto_review
- `GET /api/cron` -- Cron trigger for auto-review + stale reminders

**Pages (5 pages)**
- `/` -- Landing page with live stats bar
- `/verify` -- Application form (existing, unchanged)
- `/verify/confirm` -- Email confirmation (existing, unchanged)
- `/registry` -- Public registry with clickable profile links
- `/admin` -- Full admin dashboard with login, stats, application list, detail view, actions
- `/agent/[handle]` -- Public agent profile with badges, embed snippet

**Database (1 new migration)**
- `003_guardrails.sql` -- Adds `handle`, `requires_human_override`, `auto_review_score`, `last_action_at` columns; `audit_logs` table; `agent_jobs` table; tightened RLS insert policy; updated view

### Edge cases fixed during build
1. **Email normalization** -- `owner_email` lowercased/trimmed to prevent case-variant duplicates
2. **Agent name validation** -- Rejects names that produce empty handles (only special chars/whitespace)
3. **Email-before-DB** -- Email sent first; if it fails, no orphan record created
4. **Admin cookie security** -- Password hashed (SHA-256) before storing in cookie
5. **Handle collision** -- Suffix incrementing with limit (admin + auto-approval)
6. **Identity link validation** -- Server-side URL format check
7. **Input length limits** -- `agent_name` capped at 100 chars, `agent_description` at 2000 chars
8. **Status escalation prevention** -- RLS insert policy enforces `status = 'pending'`
9. **Auto-approval kill switch** -- `AUTO_APPROVAL_ENABLED` env var + daily cap
10. **Optimistic lock on state transitions** -- Prevents race conditions

### Deleted (stale code)
- `schema.sql` -- Legacy AgentRent schema
- `src/lib/circle.ts` -- Dormant escrow integration

### TypeScript check: **0 errors** (full check without skipLibCheck)

### What you need to do next
1. **Run migration** `003_guardrails.sql` against your Supabase project
2. **Set environment variables**: `ADMIN_PASSWORD`, `ADMIN_API_TOKEN`, `AUTOMATION_TOKEN`, `AUTO_APPROVAL_ENABLED`, `MAX_AUTO_APPROVALS_PER_DAY`
3. **Optionally run seed**: `npx tsx scripts/seed.ts` (requires Supabase env vars)
4. **Set up external cron** to hit `GET /api/cron?token=YOUR_AUTOMATION_TOKEN` every 15-30 minutes

Code updated to use Postmark. Summary:

## Postmark integration complete

### Changes made

1. Created `src/lib/email.ts` — centralized email sending via Postmark API
2. Updated `src/lib/env.ts` — changed `RESEND_API_KEY` → `POSTMARK_API_KEY`
3. Updated `src/app/api/verify/route.ts` — uses Postmark for verification emails
4. Updated `src/app/api/admin/route.ts` — uses Postmark for test task emails
5. Updated `.env.local` — placeholder for `POSTMARK_API_KEY`

### To test

1. Add your Postmark API key to `.env.local`:
   ```bash
   POSTMARK_API_KEY=your-postmark-server-token-here
   ```
   Get it from: https://account.postmarkapp.com/servers → Your Server → API Tokens

2. Restart the dev server (if running) to load the new env var

3. Test email sending:
   ```bash
   npx tsx scripts/test-email.ts your-email@example.com
   ```

4. Or test via the app:
   - Submit a verification application at `/verify` (sends verification email)
   - Or use the admin panel to send a test task email

### Postmark API details

- Endpoint: `https://api.postmarkapp.com/email`
- Auth: `X-Postmark-Server-Token` header
- From email: Uses `FROM_EMAIL` from `.env.local` (format: `AgentKYC <hello@agentkyc.io>`)

The dev server should hot-reload. Add your Postmark API key and test.
